# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Composite Pattern (Gang of Four - Structural Pattern)**
> The **Composite Design Pattern** is a *structural design pattern* defined in the seminal *Design Patterns: Elements of Reusable Object-Oriented Software* (Gamma, Helm, Johnson, Vlissides, 1994). It allows you to compose objects into **tree structures** to represent **part–whole hierarchies**. The pattern enables clients to treat **individual objects (leaves)** and **compositions of objects (composites)** **uniformly** through a *common interface*.

In KTU 2024 Scheme terminology, the Composite Pattern is a core topic under *Structural Design Patterns* and addresses the principle:

> *"Compose objects into tree structures to represent part-whole hierarchies. Composite lets clients treat individual objects and compositions uniformly."*
> — *GoF Catalog Definition*

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Analogy — The Organization Chart**
> Imagine a corporate organization chart:
> - The **CEO** is at the top.
> - Under the CEO are **Vice Presidents** (managers).
> - Under VPs are **Team Leads**, and under them are **Individual Employees**.
> - From the CEO's perspective, sending a directive ("generate monthly report") should work the **same way** whether it goes to a single employee, a team, or an entire division.

You don't want to write separate logic for "send report to one employee" vs "send report to a department with 50 employees." The Composite pattern says: **treat every node the same**. Whether the node has sub-nodes or not, the calling code does not care.

| Domain | Leaf | Composite |
|---|---|---|
| File System | File | Folder (contains Files/Folders) |
| Organization | Employee | Manager (manages Employees) |
| GUI | Button | Panel (contains Buttons/Panels) |
| Arithmetic | $2$, $x$ | $(2 + x)$ expression |

The pattern reduces the **complexity of client code** by collapsing the distinction between primitive and container objects.

## 1.3 Standard Metrics & Key Terminology

- **Structural Pattern Category:** Deals with object composition and class relationships.
- **Tree Depth:** Recursion limit — keep shallow (typically $\leq 5$–$7$) to avoid stack overflow.
- **Uniformity Principle:** Client invokes operations on `Component` interface; both `Leaf` and `Composite` inherit from it.
- **Polymorphic Dispatch:** Method calls are resolved at runtime via *dynamic binding*.
- **Recursive Composition:** A composite contains `Components` which may themselves be composites.

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 The Four Canonical Participants

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The Composite Pattern is defined by **four (4) mandatory participants** as per the Gang of Four specification:

| # | Participant | Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Component** | Abstract interface | Declares the common interface for both leaves and composites; optionally defines default behavior for child-management operations. |
| 2 | **Leaf** | Primitive element | Represents *end objects* (no children). Defines behavior for primitive objects in the composition. |
| 3 | **Composite** | Container element | Stores child components; implements child-related operations (`add`, `remove`, `getChild`). |
| 4 | **Client** | Manipulator | Manipulates objects in the composition through the `Component` interface. |

## 2.2 Operational Logic — Step-by-Step

**Step 1 — Interface Definition (Component)**
Define an abstract `Component` class/interface that exposes:
- An `operation()` method (business logic).
- Optional methods for managing children: `add(Component c)`, `remove(Component c)`, `getChild(int i)`.

**Step 2 — Leaf Implementation**
The `Leaf` class extends `Component` and implements `operation()`. It **overrides** child-management methods to throw `UnsupportedOperationException` (since leaves cannot have children).

**Step 3 — Composite Implementation**
The `Composite` class also extends `Component`. It maintains a collection (typically `ArrayList<Component>` or `Vector<Component>`) of children. Its `operation()` method **recursively delegates** to all children, then optionally aggregates their results.

**Step 4 — Client Invocation**
The client code holds a reference of type `Component`. Whether the actual object is a `Leaf` or `Composite`, calling `operation()` works seamlessly due to polymorphism.

**Why Recursion Works**

For a tree of depth $d$ with branching factor $b$, total nodes $n$ is bounded by:

$$
n \;=\; \sum_{i=0}^{d} b^{i} \;=\; \frac{b^{d+1} - 1}{b - 1}, \quad b \geq 2
$$

The `operation()` call traverses $O(n)$ nodes.

**Step 5 — Safety vs Transparency Trade-off**

There are two design philosophies in Composite:

| Approach | Child Methods Location | Pro | Con |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Transparent** | In `Component` interface | Maximum uniformity | Leaves throw `UnsupportedOperationException` |
| **Safe** | Only in `Composite` class | No runtime exceptions on leaves | Client must downcast to use composites |

The GoF book recommends the **Transparent** approach; most modern frameworks prefer the **Safe** approach for type safety.

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Equation / Rule | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Total Nodes in Balanced Tree | $n = \dfrac{b^{d+1} - 1}{b - 1}$ | Geometric series sum |
| Time Complexity of `operation()` | $O(n)$ where $n$ = total nodes | Visits every node once |
| Space Complexity (Recursive Call Stack) | $O(d)$ | $d$ = tree depth |
| Child Index Validation | $0 \leq i < \vert \text{children} \vert$ | Required pre-condition |
| Memory Footprint per Composite | $O(b)$ references | Plus the actual objects |
| Type Check Rule | `instanceof Composite` | Use only when Safe approach is followed |

> [!NOTE]
> **Critical KTU Point:** When asked to "explain the Composite pattern," examiners expect you to **explicitly name all 4 participants**, draw a UML class diagram, and discuss **transparency vs safety**. These three together fetch 4–6 marks.

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Compilers / ASTs:** Abstract Syntax Trees represent program code as a Composite — leaves are literals/identifiers, composites are expressions/statements.
- **GUI Frameworks:** Java Swing, JavaFX, Android `View`/`ViewGroup` hierarchies.
- **Document Object Model (DOM):** HTML/XML parsed into a tree of nodes where both text and element nodes implement `Node`.
- **Operating Systems:** File systems where files (leaves) and directories (composites) share the same interface.
- **Enterprise Systems:** Organization hierarchies, product category trees, menu structures.

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 3. Step-by-Step Implementation Analysis

## 3.1 Worked Example — File System Hierarchy

Let us implement the Composite pattern for a **File System** where both `File` (leaf) and `Directory` (composite) are treated uniformly.

### 3.1.1 Step 1: Define the Component Interface

```java
// Component.java
public interface FileSystemComponent {
    void showDetails(String indent);   // operation()
    default void add(FileSystemComponent c) {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Cannot add to a leaf");
    }
    default void remove(FileSystemComponent c) {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Cannot remove from a leaf");
    }
    default FileSystemComponent getChild(int i) {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Leaf has no children");
    }
}
```

**Logic Explanation:**
- The interface declares `showDetails()` — the common operation for both leaves and composites.
- The three child-management methods use Java's `default` keyword to provide a default exception-throwing implementation. Leaves inherit this default; composites override it.
- This implements the **Transparent** Composite variant.

### 3.1.2 Step 2: Implement the Leaf

```java
// File.java
public class File implements FileSystemComponent {
    private final String name;
    private final long sizeKB;

    public File(String name, long sizeKB) {
        this.name = name;
        this.sizeKB = sizeKB;
    }

    @Override
    public void showDetails(String indent) {
        System.out.println(indent + "📄 File: " + name + " (" + sizeKB + " KB)");
    }
}
```

**Logic Explanation:**
- `File` is a *terminal node* — it stores its own name and size.
- It implements `showDetails()` directly without recursion.
- It **inherits** the `default` exception-throwing implementations of `add/remove/getChild` from the interface.

### 3.1.3 Step 3: Implement the Composite

```java
// Directory.java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class Directory implements FileSystemComponent {
    private final String name;
    private final List<FileSystemComponent> children = new ArrayList<>();

    public Directory(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    @Override
    public void add(FileSystemComponent c) {
        children.add(c);
    }

    @Override
    public void remove(FileSystemComponent c) {
        children.remove(c);
    }

    @Override
    public FileSystemComponent getChild(int i) {
        return children.get(i);
    }

    @Override
    public void showDetails(String indent) {
        System.out.println(indent + "📁 Directory: " + name);
        for (FileSystemComponent child : children) {
            child.showDetails(indent + "   ");
        }
    }
}
```

**Logic Explanation:**
- The `Directory` overrides **all three** child-management methods to manipulate an internal `ArrayList`.
- Its `showDetails()` first prints its own name, then **recursively** calls `showDetails()` on each child with increased indentation.
- The recursion terminates when a `Leaf` (`File`) is reached — `File.showDetails()` has no recursive call.

### 3.1.4 Step 4: Client Code Demonstration

```java
// Client.java
public class Client {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        File f1 = new File("resume.pdf", 250);
        File f2 = new File("photo.jpg", 1800);
        File f3 = new File("notes.txt", 12);

        Directory subFolder = new Directory("Documents");
        subFolder.add(f1);
        subFolder.add(f3);

        Directory root = new Directory("Home");
        root.add(subFolder);
        root.add(f2);

        root.showDetails("");
    }
}
```

**Expected Output:**
```
📁 Directory: Home
   📁 Directory: Documents
      📄 File: resume.pdf (250 KB)
      📄 File: notes.txt (12 KB)
   📄 File: photo.jpg (1800 KB)
```

**Execution Trace — Recursion Depth Analysis:**

The total call stack depth for the largest branch of tree $d = 2$:

$$
\text{Stack Depth} \;=\; d + 1 \;=\; 3
$$

Total nodes traversed during `root.showDetails("")`:

$$
n \;=\; \sum_{i=0}^{2} 2^{i} \;=\; 1 + 2 + 1 \;=\; 4 \text{ nodes}
$$

But the *number of method invocations* is $O(2n - 1) = 7$ calls (since each internal node calls children + itself).

### 3.1.5 Step 5: Mathematical Verification of Recursion

For a balanced tree of branching factor $b = 2$ and depth $d = 2$:

$$
n = \frac{2^{2+1} - 1}{2 - 1} = \frac{8 - 1}{1} = 7
$$

This matches our tree (1 root + 1 subdirectory + 3 files + 2 implicit null children positions — but only 4 are populated, so $n_{\text{actual}} = 4$).

The general traversal cost is:

$$
T(n) \;=\; \begin{cases} 
\Theta(1) & \text{if leaf} \\
\Theta(c) + \sum_{i=1}^{k} T(\text{child}_i) & \text{if composite with } k \text{ children}
\end{cases}
$$

By induction, $T(n) = \Theta(n)$ for a tree with $n$ total nodes.

## 3.2 Analytical Matrix — Pattern Variant Comparison

| Variant | `add/remove` Location | Client Cast Required? | Exception Risk | Used In |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Transparent Composite** | `Component` (abstract) | No | `UnsupportedOperationException` | GoF reference |
| **Safe Composite** | `Composite` (concrete only) | Yes (downcast) | Compile-time safe | Modern APIs (Java AWT, Swing) |
| **Component with Default Impl** | `Component` (default methods) | No | `UnsupportedOperationException` | Java 8+ idiomatic style |
| **Static Typed Composite** | Sealed interface in Java 17 | Pattern matching | None | Modern Java/Kotlin |

<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

