# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

### Q1. **[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023, Model Question Paper]**
**Define the Composite Design Pattern. List its participants.**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Definition (2 Marks):**
> The Composite Design Pattern is a structural design pattern that allows you to compose objects into tree structures to represent part-whole hierarchies. It lets clients treat individual objects (leaves) and compositions of objects (composites) uniformly through a common interface.

> **Participants (1 Mark):**
> 1. **Component** — declares the common interface for objects in the composition.
> 2. **Leaf** — represents end objects with no children.
> 3. **Composite** — defines behavior for components having children; stores child components.
> 4. **Client** — manipulates objects in the composition via the Component interface.

*(Total: 3 Marks)*

---

### Q2. **[KTU University Exam – June 2024, Module 2]**
**Differentiate between the "Transparent" and "Safe" approaches of implementing the Composite Pattern.**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**

| Aspect | Transparent Approach | Safe Approach |
|---|---|---|
| Child management methods location | Declared in `Component` interface | Declared only in `Composite` class |
| Client-side type checking | Not required | Requires `instanceof` check or downcasting |
| Compile-time safety | Low (leaves throw `UnsupportedOperationException` at runtime) | High (compile error if misused) |
| Used in | GoF reference implementation, modern Java default methods | Java AWT `Container`, older APIs |

*(Total: 3 Marks)*

---

## 5.2 Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each, Internal Choice)

---

### 🔹 Question A — **[14 Marks, Internal Choice Option A]**

**[KTU University Exam – Dec 2022 Adapted, Module 2 Design Patterns]**

**(a)** Explain the Composite Design Pattern with a neat UML class diagram. Discuss the responsibilities of each participant. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java program to model an organization hierarchy using the Composite Pattern where `Employee` (individual) and `Department` (group) can be uniformly asked to "showDetails." **(7 Marks)**

---

### ✅ Model Answer to Q.A

#### Part (a) — Explanation with UML Diagram (7 Marks)

**Definition (2 Marks):**
The Composite Pattern composes objects into tree structures representing whole-part hierarchies. Clients treat individual objects and compositions uniformly through a common interface called `Component`.

**Participants & Responsibilities (4 Marks):**

| Participant | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| `Component` (interface) | Declares common operations like `showDetails()`; optionally declares `add/remove/getChild` for child management. |
| `Leaf` | Implements `Component` for primitive objects. Has no children. Defines behavior for end nodes. |
| `Composite` | Implements `Component` for objects having children. Stores `Component` children in a collection. Implements child-management methods. Its `operation()` delegates recursively to children. |
| `Client` | Holds a `Component` reference and invokes operations. Due to polymorphism, the client code is independent of whether the object is a leaf or composite. |

**UML Class Diagram (1 Mark):** [Refer to Section 4.1 diagram]

**Total: 7 Marks**

---

#### Part (b) — Java Implementation (7 Marks)

```java
// Component.java
interface OrganizationUnit {
    void showDetails(String indent);
    default void add(OrganizationUnit unit) {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Not supported");
    }
    default void remove(OrganizationUnit unit) {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Not supported");
    }
}

// Leaf.java - Employee
class Employee implements OrganizationUnit {
    private String name;
    private String role;
    public Employee(String name, String role) {
        this.name = name; this.role = role;
    }
    @Override
    public void showDetails(String indent) {
        System.out.println(indent + "👤 " + name + " (" + role + ")");
    }
}

// Composite.java - Department
class Department implements OrganizationUnit {
    private String name;
    private java.util.List<OrganizationUnit> members = new java.util.ArrayList<>();
    public Department(String name) { this.name = name; }
    @Override
    public void add(OrganizationUnit u) { members.add(u); }
    @Override
    public void remove(OrganizationUnit u) { members.remove(u); }
    @Override
    public void showDetails(String indent) {
        System.out.println(indent + "🏢 Department: " + name);
        for (OrganizationUnit u : members) {
            u.showDetails(indent + "    ");
        }
    }
}

// Client.java
public class OrgClient {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee e1 = new Employee("Arjun", "Developer");
        Employee e2 = new Employee("Meera", "Tester");

        Department devTeam = new Department("Development");
        devTeam.add(e1);
        devTeam.add(e2);

        Employee e3 = new Employee("Rahul", "Manager");

        Department itDept = new Department("IT Department");
        itDept.add(e3);
        itDept.add(devTeam);    // Composite inside composite

        itDept.showDetails("");
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
🏢 Department: IT Department
    👤 Rahul (Manager)
    🏢 Department: Development
        👤 Arjun (Developer)
        👤 Meera (Tester)
```

**Evaluation Rubric (7 Marks):**

- Correct Component interface: **2 Marks**
- Leaf implementation: **1.5 Marks**
- Composite implementation with recursion: **2.5 Marks**
- Client code demonstrating uniform usage: **1 Mark**

**Total: 7 Marks**

---

### 🔹 Question B — **[14 Marks, Internal Choice Option B]**

**[KTU University Exam – June 2023 Adapted, Module 2 Design Patterns]**

**(a)** Discuss the Composite Design Pattern with a real-world example. How does it represent part-whole hierarchies? What are its advantages and disadvantages? **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Compare and contrast the Composite Pattern with the Decorator Pattern. Give one real-world scenario where each is most appropriate. **(7 Marks)**

---

### ✅ Model Answer to Q.B

#### Part (a) — Composite Pattern Discussion (7 Marks)

**Real-world Example (2 Marks):**
**Graphic Systems** — A drawing application allows users to group shapes (circles, rectangles, lines) into a single drawing. The drawing itself can be grouped with other drawings. Both a single shape and a group of shapes must respond to operations like `draw()`, `move()`, `resize()`.

**Part-Whole Hierarchy Representation (2 Marks):**
The Composite pattern models hierarchical tree structures where:
- The **whole** (e.g., a `Group` of shapes) and the **part** (e.g., a `Circle`) expose the **same interface**.
- Operations performed on the whole are **automatically propagated** to all parts via recursive delegation.
- The tree depth and branching factor can be arbitrary — the structure is **open-ended** and **dynamic**.

**Advantages (1.5 Marks):**
1. Simplifies client code — uniform interface for primitives and composites.
2. Easy to add new component types — *Open/Closed Principle*.
3. Represents complex tree structures naturally.

**Disadvantages (1.5 Marks):**
1. Can over-generalize the API (leaves get unused methods).
2. Difficult to restrict component types in a composite (e.g., a `Folder` that should only contain `File`s).
3. Recursion can cause stack overflow on very deep trees.

**Total: 7 Marks**

---

#### Part (b) — Composite vs Decorator (7 Marks)

| Aspect | Composite Pattern | Decorator Pattern |
|---|---|---|
| **Intent** | Compose objects into tree structures | Add behavior to objects dynamically without subclassing |
| **Structure** | Tree (whole-part) | Layered wrapper (single object) |
| **Number of objects at runtime** | Multiple (tree of objects) | Single wrapped object |
| **Purpose** | Represent hierarchies | Extend functionality |
| **Recursion** | Yes — composites delegate to children | No — decorators wrap and forward to one component |
| **Typical Use Case** | File systems, organization trees | Adding scrollbars to windows, adding encryption to streams |

**Real-World Scenarios (3 Marks — 1.5 each):**

1. **Composite Best For:** A *menu system* in a GUI application — menu items can be leaf items or sub-menus that contain more items; both need to respond to `render()` and `click()` uniformly.

2. **Decorator Best For:** A *Java I/O stream* — start with a `FileInputStream`, wrap it with a `BufferedInputStream` for buffering, then wrap with an `EncryptionInputStream` for security. Each decorator adds functionality without modifying the underlying stream.

**Total: 7 Marks**

---

## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mistakes that COST MARKS in KTU Examinations:**
> 1. **Forgetting the `Client` participant** — Most students name only Component, Leaf, and Composite. The Client is **mandatory** in the GoF definition and worth 1 mark.
> 2. **Confusing Composite with Decorator** — Both are structural, but Composite is **recursive (tree)** while Decorator is **layered (chain)**. Examiners often ask this comparison.
> 3. **Not drawing the aggregation arrow** — In the UML diagram, the relationship `Composite o--> Component` (aggregation) must be shown with a **diamond at the Composite end**. Drawing a plain line loses 1 mark.
> 4. **Writing recursive method body without base case** — In code questions, always show the *leaf case* (no recursive call) before the *composite case* (recursive call). This signals understanding.
> 5. **Using `ArrayList<Component>` without explaining polymorphism** — Always add a one-line comment/note explaining "this collection stores both Leaf and Composite polymorphically."

## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist — Composite Pattern**
>
> - ✅ **Category:** Gang of Four (GoF) **Structural** Pattern
> - ✅ **Intent:** Compose objects into tree structures to represent part-whole hierarchies uniformly.
> - ✅ **4 Participants:** `Component` (interface), `Leaf` (terminal), `Composite` (container), `Client` (user)
> - ✅ **Key Mechanism:** Recursive delegation; **polymorphism** via common interface
> - ✅ **Two Variants:** Transparent (child methods in `Component`) vs. Safe (only in `Composite`)
> - ✅ **UML Notation:** Hollow triangle = realization; hollow diamond = aggregation
> - ✅ **Time Complexity:** $O(n)$ for tree traversal, where $n$ = total nodes
> - ✅ **Space Complexity:** $O(d)$ for call stack, where $d$ = tree depth
> - ✅ **When to Use:** When you need to represent hierarchies of objects and ignore the difference between primitives and containers in client code.
> - ✅ **When NOT to Use:** When the hierarchy is fixed and shallow, or when primitives and containers need fundamentally different APIs.
> - ✅ **Real-world Examples:** File systems, GUI component trees, organization charts, ASTs in compilers, DOM trees.
> - ✅ **Related GoF Patterns:** Often combined with **Iterator** (to traverse the tree), **Visitor** (to apply operations), and **Decorator** (to add behavior to leaves).
> - ✅ **Common Mistake to Avoid:** Saying "Composite is just inheritance" — it is **composition over inheritance**, which is the *entire* GoF philosophy.

<!-- SECTION_5_END -->
